<p class="home-name">Mohammed Alkharraz</p>

<p>
  I'm a Digital Solutions Engineer at <a href="https://www.weatherford.com">Weatherford</a>,
  working in oil and gas, on the side that asks how it could run better.
</p>

<p>
  My work sits at the intersection of <strong>production optimization</strong>,
  <strong>artificial lift systems</strong>, <strong>data analytics</strong>,
  <strong>AI/ML</strong>, and <strong>automation</strong>. I build and drive the solutions
  that connect physical operations with digital execution, across every well and facility
  in the field, to enhance production, maximize uptime, and improve efficiency.
</p>

<p>
  A lot of it is bridging two worlds that don't naturally speak to each other: the field,
  where wells and facilities behave in messy physical ways, and the software that's supposed
  to make sense of them. I spend my time closing that gap, making stubborn systems actually
  work, finding the solution and making it stick, so a dynacard or a pressure trend stops
  being noise and becomes something you can act on. Occasionally that just means figuring
  out why something that should work doesn't. There's a satisfaction to that last part
  that's hard to explain.
</p>

<p>
  Outside of work I'm an athlete, I train martial arts and I like to cook, and sometimes
  tinker with technology. I also read philosophy, mostly the kind that doesn't offer clean
  answers, and take things apart to understand how they work.
  People, systems, ideas. Sometimes I put them back together.
</p>

